ss enthusiasts look at training the core or \u201cabs\u201d as performing crunches or sit-ups. However, the majority of the core\u2019s responsibility is to REMOVE movement, not create it. This is why the majority of our core stability training is with a variety of planks, side planks, and hollow holds, instead of constant flexion of the spine.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Warm-up:</h2>\n<p>RUNNING @80% effort<br>\n1x 200m<br>\n1x400m<br>\n1x600m</p>\n<h2>Stability</h2>\n<p>Tabata: Hollow Holds</p>\n<h2>MetCon:</h2>\n<p><strong>AMRAP 12</strong><br>\n100\u2019 Bear Crawl (4x 25\u2019 = across and back twice) (every 25\u2019 = 5 reps)<br>\n30 DB Snatches 50/35#<br>\n*50 reps per round</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</div><!--article-content-wrap-->\r\n\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t   \r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t</div>"}
