{"all": "<div class=\"content-inner\">\r\n\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t\t<a href=\"http://crossfitonthehill.com/wod/wod-122316\"><span class=\"post-featured-img\"><img width=\"4032\" height=\"3024\" src=\"http://crossfitonthehill.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/rowing.jpg\" class=\"attachment-full size-full wp-post-image\" alt=\"\" title=\"\" srcset=\"http://crossfitonthehill.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/rowing.jpg 4032w, http://crossfitonthehill.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/rowing-300x225.jpg 300w, http://crossfitonthehill.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/rowing-768x576.jpg 768w, http://crossfitonthehill.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/rowing-1024x768.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 4032px) 100vw, 4032px\"></span></a>\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"article-content-wrap\">\r\n\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"post-header\">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<h2 class=\"title\">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t \r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<a href=\"http://crossfitonthehill.com/wod/wod-122316\">\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tWOD for Friday, 12/23/16\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t </a> \r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</h2>\r\n\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t \r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class=\"meta-author\"><span>By</span> <a href=\"http://crossfitonthehill.com/author/admin\" title=\"Posts by CrossFit on the Hill\" rel=\"author\">CrossFit on the Hill</a></span> <span class=\"meta-category\">| <a href=\"http://crossfitonthehill.com/category/strength-programming\">Strength Programming</a>, <a href=\"http://crossfitonthehill.com/category/wod\">WOD</a></span> <span class=\"meta-comment-count\">| <a href=\"http://crossfitonthehill.com/wod/wod-122316#respond\">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tNo Comments</a></span>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</div><!--/post-header-->\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p>Today our conditioning is rowing 2,000 meters for time. We can\u2019t think of all the rowing tests as the same. Speed, stroke rate, mechanics, and power output should be considered and varied when performing a 500m, 1000m or 2,000m row. The shorter a row the closer an athlete can work to his or her anaerobic threshold simply because the distance may be completed before the body hits its capacity to still perform the work. Longer distances require an athlete to understand what a good pace is short of burning out but fast enough to submit a good time. The best way of know such speeds is to row these distances often and condition your body to them.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Strength Circuit:</h2>\n<p><strong>4 Rounds: (15mins)</strong><br>\n10 Ring Dips<br>\n10 (each) Bulgarian Split Squat<br>\n10 Single Arm DB Row</p>\n<h2>Fitness Test:</h2>\n<p>For time: 2K Row</p>\n<h2>Cash Out: (7mins)</h2>\n<p>Perform in Partners:<br>\n5 Rounds (each) *10 rounds total<br>\n30 sec Hanging Knee Raise Hold weighted w/ Plate<br>\n-10sec transition</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</div><!--article-content-wrap-->\r\n\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t   \r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t</div>"}
